{{hatnote|Not to be confused with the [[Hobart and William Smith Colleges#Elizabeth Blackwell Award|Elizabeth Blackwell Award]] presented by Hobart and William Smith Colleges.}} The '''Elizabeth Blackwell Medal''' is awarded annually by the [[American Medical Women's Association]]. The medal is named in honor of [[Elizabeth Blackwell]], the first woman to receive a medical degree in the United States and a pioneer in promoting the education of [[women in medicine]]. Established by Elise S. L'Esperance in 1949, 100 years after Blackwell received her medical degree,<ref>{{cite web|title=Elizabeth Blackwell Letters, circa 1850-1884|url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/lweb/archival/collections/ldpd_4079307/|publisher=Columbia University Libraries|accessdate=10 May 2013}}</ref> the medal is granted to a woman physician "who has made the most outstanding contributions to the cause of women in the field of medicine." Before 1993, the medal was only awarded to members of the AMWA.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elizabeth Blackwell Award|url=http://www.amwa-doc.org/awards/elizabeth-blackwell|publisher=American Medical Women's Association|accessdate=10 May 2013}}</ref> [[File:Elizabeth blackwell stamp.JPG|thumb|Elizabeth blackwell stamp]] [[File:Elizabeth Blackwell.jpg|thumb|[[Elizabeth Blackwell]]]][[File:Esther Pohl Lovejoy.jpg|thumb|[[Esther Pohl Lovejoy]] received the award in 1951 and 1957.]] [[File:TinaStrobos1941.jpg|thumb|Dr. [[Tina Strobos]] was co-recipient of the award in 1998. ]]
