The '''Milk River''' is a tributary of the [[Missouri River]], {{convert|729|mi|km|abbr=on}} long, in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Montana]] and the [[Canadian province]] of [[Alberta]]. Rising in the [[Rocky Mountains]], the river drains a sparsely populated, semi-arid [[Drainage basin|watershed]] of {{convert|23800|mi2|km2|abbr=on|0}}, ending just east of [[Fort Peck, Montana]].
==Geography== It is formed in [[Glacier County, Montana|Glacier County]] in northwestern Montana, {{convert|21|mi|km}} north of [[Browning, Montana]], by the confluence of its South and Middle forks. The {{convert|30|mi|km|adj=on}} long South Fork and {{convert|20|mi|km|adj=on}} long Middle Fork both rise in the [[Rocky Mountains]] just east of [[Glacier National Park (U.S.)|Glacier National Park]], in the [[Blackfeet Indian Reservation]]. {{citation needed|date=March 2016}} Much of the water in the North Fork is diverted from the [[St. Mary River (Alberta-Montana)|St. Mary River]] through a canal and inverted siphon.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usbr.gov/projects/Project.jsp?proj_Name=Milk+River+Project |title=Milk River Project |publisher=[[Milk River Watershed Council Canada]] |accessdate=2017-10-16}}</ref>
The main stream flows east-northeast into southern Alberta, where it is joined by the [[North Fork of the Milk River]], from there It flows past the town of [[Milk River, Alberta|Milk River]] and [[Writing-on-Stone Provincial Park]], then turns southeast into Montana, running east along the north side of the [[Sweetgrass Hills]], turning south, passing through the [[Fresno Dam]], then east past [[Havre, Montana|Havre]] and along the north side of the [[Fort Belknap Indian Reservation]]. Near [[Malta, Montana|Malta]], it turns north, then southeast, flowing past [[Glasgow, Montana|Glasgow]] and joining the Missouri in [[Valley County, Montana]], {{convert|5|mi|km|0}} downstream from [[Fort Peck Dam]]. {{citation needed|date=March 2016}}
The watershed of the river extends into the Canadian provinces of Alberta and [[Saskatchewan]] and the US state of Montana. The watershed of the river covers an area of {{convert|61642|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}. Of this {{convert|6500|km2|mi2|abbr=on|0}} lies in Alberta, {{convert|14942|km2|mi2|abbr=on}} in Saskatchewan and the remaining in Montana.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mrwcc.ca/index.php/watershed/overview-milk-river-watershed/ |title=Overview of the Milk River Watershedt |publisher=[[U.S. Bureau of Reclamation]] |date=2011-05-11 |accessdate=2011-10-28}}</ref> The area in Alberta and Saskatchewan is a part of the [[Mississippi River]] watershed that extends into Canada.
==History== The Milk River was given its name by Captain [[Meriwether Lewis]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lewisandclarkjournals.unl.edu/read/?_xmlsrc=1805-05-08.xml&_xslsrc=LCstyles.xsl | title=The Journals of the Lewis and Clark Expedition | publisher=University of Nebraska|accessdate=2016-12-04}}</ref> of the [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]], who described the river in his journal:
:''"the water of this river possesses a peculiar whiteness, being about the colour of a cup of tea with the admixture of a tablespoonfull of milk. from the colour of its water we called it Milk river."''
This appearance results from clays and silts suspended in its waters. These fine-grained sediments result from the erosion of soft clay-rich rocks along the Milk River basin in southern Alberta, such as the [[Foremost Formation|Foremost]], [[Oldman Formation|Oldman]] and [[Dinosaur Park Formation|Dinosaur Park]] [[Formation (stratigraphy)|formations]].<ref name="Map600">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ags.gov.ab.ca/publications/pubs.aspx?series=map|title=Bedrock Geology of Alberta. Alberta Geological Survey, Map 600|author=Prior, G. J., Hathaway, B., Glombick, P.M., Pana, D.I., Banks, C.J., Hay, D.C., Schneider, C.L., Grobe, M., Elgr, R., and Weiss, J.A.|year=2013|accessdate=2013-08-13|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130925225910/http://www.ags.gov.ab.ca/publications/pubs.aspx?series=map|archivedate=2013-09-25|df=}}</ref>
{{wide image|Milkriverpan.jpg|750px|align-cap=center|The Milk River in [[Writing-on-Stone Provincial Park]]}}
At the time of Lewis's exploration, the Milk River drainage was legally part of the United States as a component of the [[Louisiana Purchase]]. However, in 1818 U.S. negotiators [[Anglo-American Convention of 1818|swapped a portion]] of the Milk River watershed that lay north of 49° north latitude, receiving in exchange a parcel of [[Red River of the North]] drainage that had previously been part of [[British North America]]. {{citation needed|date=July 2015}}
In 1908, the waters of the Milk River were the subject of a [[United States Supreme Court]] case clarifying the [[water rights]] of American [[Indian reservations]]. The case is known as ''[[Winters v. United States]]''.
