{{italic title}} '''''What's New?''''' was an American daily science and entertainment television program for children.<ref>[http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1963/08/25/page/132/article/whats-new-show-called-whats-new Wolters, Larry. "What's New? Show Called ''What's New''" (''Chicago Tribune'', August 25, 1963, TV Section 5, p.14)]</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19670219&id=YgorAAAAIBAJ&sjid=95kFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4719,1873297&hl=en ''What's New?'' programming schedule {with daily mention of George Fischbeck and Murl Deusing} for Monday, February 20 through Friday, February 24, 1967 on Pennsylvania educational station WITF, channel 33 in Reading (''Reading Eagle'', February 19, 1967, TV section, p.4)]</ref> The [[National Educational Television]] (NET) network and its 1970 successor, the [[Public Broadcasting System]] (PBS) broadcast the show from 1962 to 1973.<ref name=Binford>[http://www.foxvalleyarts.org/binford.htm "J. Allison (Al) Binford Jr." (''Fox Valley Arts Hall of Fame'')]</ref> The half-hour program aired in [[black-and-white]] and, as of October 1967, in color.<ref name="WQLN 1967">{{cite web |url=http://www.wqln.org/main/About%20WQLN/WQLN%20History%20Project/default.aspx |title=How well do you remember August 1967? |work=Wqln.org |publisher=[[WQLN (TV)]] |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100205043322/http://www.wqln.org/main/About%20WQLN/WQLN%20History%20Project/default.aspx |archivedate=2010-02-05 |accessdate=2016-04-06 }}</ref><ref name="Watson">Mary Ann Watson,"The expanding vista: American television in the Kennedy years," Durham, NC, Duke University Press, 1994, p. 186</ref>
The target audience was upper elementary school and junior high school grades. The show was hosted by Al Binford,<ref name=Binford/> with daily segments presented by science teacher [[George Fischbeck]],<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=FrCkc8_mLz4C&pg=PT46&lpg=PT46&dq=George+Fischbeck+National+Educational+Television&source=bl&ots=fLi2wz2KlK&sig=1MnuaEEoEkUA3c_nP51qHX9cyns&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwie_IrU8-rNAhUMND4KHW2AD0gQ6AEIXDAI#v=onepage&q=George%20Fischbeck%20National%20Educational%20Television&f=false Fischbeck, George. ''Dr. George: My Life in Weather'' {Chapter 3: "My Classroom Expands" is devoted to his work at NET} UNM Press, 2013]</ref><ref>[http://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-dr-george-fischbeck-20150325-story.html "'Dr. George' Fischbeck dies at 92; popular weatherman at KABC–TV (''Los Angeles Times'', March 25, 2015)]</ref><ref name="WQLN 1967"/> naturalist Murl Deusing and others, including deaf mime actor [[Bernard Bragg]] whose silent semi-comical educational adventure sketches were based on the artistry of his teacher, [[Marcel Marceau]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=PrPMTDdlm1AC&pg=PA107&dq=Deaf+mime+Bernard+Bragg+on+What's+New+National+Educational+Television&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiHt8aZ8OrNAhXLHT4KHex0CU0Q6AEIMjAC#v=onepage&q=Deaf%20mime%20Bernard%20Bragg%20on%20What's%20New%20National%20Educational%20Television&f=false Bragg, Bernard as signed to Bergman, Eugene. ''Lessons in Laughter / The Autobiography of a Deaf Actor''. Gallaudet University Press, 2002]</ref> Ron Finley created the opening credits. Each program would deal with three different topics, such as baseball or space science.<ref name="WQLN 1967"/><ref name="Watson"/>
